{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654517"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18619"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18619"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79492"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11351"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64814"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10225"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27188"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79492"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe synovial joint between the first (atlas) and second (axis) cervical vertebrae enables head rotation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of joint at this location?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ball and socket","Hinge","Pivot","Plane","Saddle"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe joint between C1 and C2 vertebrae is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epivot joint\u003C/strong\u003E, where a projection from one bone rotates within a ring formed by another bone and its associated ligament. This specific arrangement enables rotational movements of the head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect joint types are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBall and socket joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Permits movement in multiple planes with a spherical head fitting into a cup-shaped socket, as seen in the hip\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHinge joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Allows movement in a single plane only, similar to the elbow\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaddle joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Features reciprocal concave-convex surfaces, exemplified by the base of the thumb\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlane joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Contains flat articulating surfaces that allow sliding movements, like those between the small bones of the wrist\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe transverse ligament provides crucial stability by securing the dens against the anterior portion of C1, while still allowing the necessary rotational movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pivot joints permit rotational movement around a central axis through a ligament-stabilized ring structure.","The joint between the first and second cervical vertebrae is a classic example of a pivot joint.","Rotation of the head occurs as C1 moves around the dens of C2."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64814"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18619"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64814"},"attributes":{"createdA